[@"Description of Lars Squiggle playing solitaire"]
[@ "I'm going to cut back to Lars squiggle and have him be playing solitaire, observing the thrilling action of a man playing a game which is literally called patience" —M ~M]

  Although it would not help him in his future career of playing poker against space aliens — or *would* it? — Lars Squiggle was currently playing solitaire. They called the game Solitaire on Skoios, although perhaps most parts of the world would call it Klondike Patience. Nevertheless, he found the calm inevitability of the cards soothing. He played with a variant set of rules that allowed him to win every time, with no mathematically impossible set-ups or branch points, through the use of additional slots, and power-ups, and a scoring system like golf that he was technically operating under but never bothered to track. He played in the bath, completely naked and extremely hot[^1], in whatever hotel-like alcove he could find in the backrooms, resting his legs.
  *Damn, I should have been an actor,* though Lars, for approximately no reason.

[^1]: In more ways than one ;)

---

  Thomas seeth't[$sooth?] at the contents of the computer, scowling, dwelling, etc. As Bus Gurton stood there motionless, Thomas redoubled his previous, almost-offhanded fixation on deduction, the most niggardly[@ it's just an innocent word] and risible[@ I'm more taken aback by ‘risible’, honestly. Why risible? I guess Holmsian deductions can be sort of funny... ~C [@ Sometimes something is so pathetic you just have to laugh at it ~M]] of the -ductions. Actually, it was a pet peeve of his that detectives seemed to refer to their skill at crime-figgering as "deduction" when any child knew that deduction was about making logically necessary conclusions from certain or at least hypothetical facts — sort of the opposite of what detectives did. Which was closer, when you got right down to it, to induction (inference from past examples), or even more accurately, abduction (inference to the best explanation) — which term's double-meaning was quite pleasing and obvious.
  Anyway, as a practitioner of the *sui generis* (or so he had often assumed) art of Trackduction, Thomas was seething because the Track was now forcing him to play a difficult game of solitaire. Freed from his jiggery-pokery about mart.ini, he had then checked out (at Track's "suggestion") martin.ini in the aforementioned "folder" but, eventually found, as he then declared aloud: "it's just some nonsense about some guy who is deceased now, who cares".
  He then felt it Would Be A Good Idea (Track Track) to click on the "icon" of a playing card (the king of hearts, for those of you keeping score at home) in the same "folder", which then greeted him with a "splash screen" reading Solly Tare Presents: Klondike Solitude, and after that a skeuomorph[@ What a terrific word! Adding it to the archives. ~C] of a playing card table, on which he felt compelled to crank the difficulty to Maximum Expert and then blast. And now the game of solitaire was very hard.
  Cursing under his breath at the solitaire gods, he then "alt-tabbed" back to the folder for a moment and lighted upon a "thumbnail" image in the folder of a "file" labelled "Attractive woman.jpg", on which he then did a click.
  [@ "Attractive woman.jpg."]
  [@ "with barely-contained horniness, but ultimately very little clues?"]
  We now use patented flash*into* technology to take you into a scene connected to the picture, presumably in the past, concerning the woman pictured therein, with the woman, as the subject of the scene. The scene takes place in the Backrooms[^2], although the picture seems to be from outside in nature. Wait a minute, “seems”? Whom does it seem to?[@ ‘To whom does it seem’, surely? ~C ❡ You have no idea of my level of power ~M[@ Interestingly, the linguistic pattern here is that people who use the who/whom distinction also tend to unstrand their prepositions, which latter practice I find completely unobjectionable but silly to insist upon as a putative grammatical obligation (and so I feel free to not do it). Feel free to draw a 2×2 matrix in your mind about this. ~M]] You? Are you a character in the novel, such that the narration can describe seemings to you, to pierce your — ah, here is Thomas to save use from this metaphysical conundrum. He is examining the background of the photograph (looking vaguely for clues) and it seems to him that it was taken outside, in nature. The possibility that it may have been taken in the Backrooms is far from his mind, but it's still a determinate (fictional) fact that if that possibility had come into his mind, he would have decided against it; dismissed it, even. Nevertheless, the scene we are flashing into is set in the Backrooms.[^3] We're still not into the scene yet. Ok, here it is. We are now into the scene.[^@mr]
  [^@mr]: Many readers (2 of 2 of my current coäuthors) seem to interpret this flashinto as implying that the previous two scenes of Lars in the Backrooms in this chapter were much earlier chronologically than they had seemed at first & took place right before the meeting with Gloria. This was not my intention, although it's ambiguous as written and ultimately doesn't matter. ~M
  “I've never seen anyone else here in the Backrooms,” said the woman who would later be photographed with a digital camera or perhaps by a non-digital[^4] camera whose print would then be scanned.
  “I'm quite surprised as well,” said Lars Squiggle, “what are the odds!”
  “Infinitesimal,” said the woman. “That's why I've taken to walking around the Backrooms with no clothes.”
  “Me either,” agreed Lars Squiggle, a bit incoherently.
  “Of course, it makes slipping into these warm, inexplicable, pools of water and baths around here quite easy,”
  “Quite,” said Lars Squiggle, who was bathing in one such now.
  “And I find the sensation of slipping between those two fluids[^5] — the warm water and the only-slightly-warm air, I mean — and slowly drying off or suddenly enmoisting myself — they both create a delightfully challenging *frisson*, don't you agree?”
  “I do so agree,” intoned Lars Squiggle, rising from his puddle for just one such embracher[@ Idk what this word is. Maybe I meant the obsolete "embrace" sense of embrasure? But as it stands I've just coined a word here for no particular reason.].
  “Still, I only take such liberties from time to time, and usually on cold winter days when I wish[@ it seems to me that we're missing a ‘to’ after this word. ~C ❡ That's just how they talk. It's their culture. ~M] conceptualize the Backrooms as more of a Bath or a natural(?) Hot Springs than a mysterious labyrinth of the peak of human civilization.”
  “I agree completely,” said Lars Squiggle. He was standing on a plane with her now, towering hugely about half a head over her because men are generally a bit taller than women,[@ Perhaps in the strange time of the Islands, this comma is unnecessary. Perhaps men are generally slightly steaming. We could only wish. ~C] and slightly steaming.
  “It sure would be a shame if someone were to find me in one of these rare states and… take advantage of me…” she said.
  “You haven't to worry about that, young miss, as I am very old and haven't the **appetites** anymore.”[@ this phrasing is something John Mulaney pretends Bill Clinton says, in one of his standup specials]
  “Oh,” she said, somewhat disappointed. “That's somewhat disappointing.”
  “The life is a vale of mild disappointments,” opined Lars Squiggle. “And, besides…” he began to monologue (you know how old people are) “back in my home culture we had mixed bathing all the time and it wasn't a problem. I'm all for people having the right to not do that, if they don't feel comfortable with it, believe me, but back in my home culture we did it all the time, and it was civilized, and largely entirely non-sexual, and it was *fine*, and I find other cultures that can't support such a thing vaguely ridiculous and uncivilized.”
  She nodded in conversational agreement, looking pretty put out. Her goosebumps were almost entirely faded by now.
  “You seem like a fine young lady; would you like to accompany me in conversation around the Backrooms? You could monologue some of the time as well.”
  She smiled a little sadly. “I think I would like that, yes.”
  “I know!: we can make our way, ambling, 17 miles to the dress-up room, stopping for lunch and dinner along the way, and then put on some fancy clothes and have our pictures taken in front of some deceptive backdrops, and have novelty pictures printed with and without the slogan superimposed ‘I went to the Backrooms and it doesn't seem that bad?’, and you can tell me all about any current developments in the spirit of the world you happen to know about…[@ what? ~C]” they were already walking that way.
  “I can tell you about my husband, who died,” she said.
  “Perfect!” exclaimed Lars, careful not to rush.
  And so they did that.

  “I'd like to explore *her* backrooms, if you know what I mean,” quipped[$ Quop] Bus.[$ If you listen carefully, you can hear whine of the flash*into* machine winding down. Uh oh, the pronoun ‘you’[$ And I only barely avoided using ‘I’.[$ Shoot.[@ I think using the actual swear would have been funnier, but alas. ~C]] Though at the beginning of the flashed*into* introductory paragraph the pronoun ‘we’ was used, so who knows.] was used again, without a buffer detective buffer to damp the narrative and quasi-existential conundra. Oh well. ~C]
  “What… what causes you to say this?” asked Thomas.
  “Oh, no reason,” admitted Bus.[$ although, secretly, and often quite obviously, he often suspected (smugly, often, it must be said) there *was* a reason, just one he wasn't privy to — one of his less-attractive traits.]

  “Hold on,” said Thomas, “while I've enjoyed looking at the slightly blurry picture of a modestly-dressed woman with ample but tasteful cleavage, my Track Sense™ is tingling. This might be… a clue!”
  “Oh,” said Guɯ̽͡s; “then you had better print it. In case we need it later.”
  “Good thinking, old chap,” said Thomas. He called up the “print dialog”[$ Better to live as patio furniture than dialog, as they say.[$ ‘They’ appears to be alright, for some reason. ~C] ~C[@ lol ~M]][sic], then tapped around. “Ok. I’ve ‘printed’ it to ‘PDF’. Wherever that is.”
  “Sounds good to me,” said Gurs.
  “Alright,” said Thomas. “my head is clear and my faith in Almighty God is restored. I will now go back to the Solitaire.”
  “Great,” said βυς, unaware that this was island slang for “Great God Almighty, have mercy on me, a cool skateboarder” (he wasn't cool enough to know this[$ though an avid and skilled skateboarder. This is now canon. ~C]).
  Thomas put(t)ered away.
  “Try putting the black four on the black five,” suggested Bʊ̈ʂ, after a minute.
  “Bussy, that's about the most ridiculous misinterpretation of the rules of solitaire I’ve ever— oh, it worked. Thanks, dude.”
  “Np.” Said ʙo̞͜øᵊç, well-aware that this was island-slang for “NaPkin” (“napkin”) — itself a phrase that meant “no problem”.
  On the screen a little rainbow text strobed and bobbed. “Congratulations! You have one[sic] at solitaire! Click "ok", below, to accept your fate.”
  *How ominous,* thought Thomas, and clicked.

